{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Many definitions of critical thinking have been put forward by scholars.",
    "According to Dewey (1916, pp. 8-14), critical thinking starts with a question, and the end product is one's ability to explain the subject in question.",
    "According to McPeck (1981, pp. 1-21), critical thinking cannot be considered as an isolated skill, but it is tied to specific subjects or activities.",
    "Chemistry education is where these skills are intensely used given the discipline's reliance on empirical evidence, problem-solving, and interpretation of experimental results.",
    "Ennis (1989, pp. 6-7) defined critical thinking as \"the correct assessing of statements\" and he differentiated between \"three dimensions of critical thinking -logical (judging the alleged relationships between the meanings of words and statements), criteria (covers the knowledge of the criteria for judging), and pragmatic (impression of the background purpose on the judgment)\"."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "According to Dewey (1916, pp. 8-14), critical thinking starts with a question, and the end product is one's ability to explain the subject in question.",
    "According to McPeck (1981, pp. 1-21), critical thinking cannot be considered as an isolated skill, but it is tied to specific subjects or activities.",
    "Ennis (1989, pp. 6-7) defined critical thinking as \"the correct assessing of statements\" and he differentiated between \"three dimensions of critical thinking -logical (judging the alleged relationships between the meanings of words and statements), criteria (covers the knowledge of the criteria for judging), and pragmatic (impression of the background purpose on the judgment)\"."
  ]
